item.title: Scientists: Artificial Intelligence Can Be Harmful and Helpful to Humans
item.description:
Scientists: Artificial Intelligence Can Be Harmful and Helpful to Humans

Artificial intelligence no longer simply exists in science fiction movies and books. From self-driving cars to intelligent computers to help doctors, these technologies are already being developed. At the Milken Institute Global Conference in Los Angeles, scientists discussed the benefits and dangers of artificial intelligence and how it will change the world.

item.title: Son of Former Pakistani PM Thanks Rescuers
item.description:
Son of Former Pakistani PM Thanks Rescuers

The son of a former Pakistani prime minister has left Afghanistan after being held by Al-Qaeda militants for three years. Ali Haider Gilani, the son of ex-premier Yusuf Raza Gilani, was freed in a joint operation by Afghan and U.S. commandos near the border with Pakistan on May 10.

item.title: Russian Television's Coverage Of Biker Club's Prague Visit
item.description:
Russian Television's Coverage Of Biker Club's Prague Visit

A pro-Kremlin motorcycle club, Night Wolves, arrived in Prague's Wenceslas Square on May 7 to a jeering, angry crowd that included Czechs, Russians, and Ukrainians. Activists from Open Russia, founded by Russian opposition figure Mikhail Khodorkovsky, covered the event. item.title: US Presidential Hopefuls Sour on Free Trade
item.description:
US Presidential Hopefuls Sour on Free Trade

As the presumptive Republican presidential nominee, Donald Trump's pronouncements are receiving a new level of scrutiny in the United States and beyond. VOA's Michael Bowman reports, Trump, as well as Democratic contenders Hillary Clinton and Bernie Sanders, have all spoken out against the Trans-Pacific Partnership in a year when few defended free trade on the presidential campaign trail.

item.title: Moldovan Socialists Protest U.S. Military Display On Victory Day
item.description:
Moldovan Socialists Protest U.S. Military Display On Victory Day

U.S. forces organized an exhibition of military vehicles and equipment in the Moldova capital, Chisinau, on May 8, the day commemorating the end of World War II in Europe. Supporters of the opposition Socialist Party protested against the display, chanting "NATO, go home," and "We don't want war."
